So, let's talk about big-S  

844
01:15:58,840 --> 01:16:05,360
strategy. When should you approach strategy 
this way and what are just the steps of it?

845
01:16:06,680 --> 01:16:14,840
So everything we've spoken about so far is what I 
would call small S, and it's very problem focused.  

846
01:16:14,840 --> 01:16:18,960
It's basically what I call present forward.
It's like you have something, you have a product  

847
01:16:18,960 --> 01:16:24,200
out there, it has a bunch of problems. How do we 
make it better for... What are the areas we tackle  

848
01:16:24,200 --> 01:16:30,280
for maximum impact? Typically led by product 
managers. And there's this interesting quote  

849
01:16:30,280 --> 01:16:37,960
by Elon Musk, which is, "Life has to be about 
more than just solving problems." And he says  

850
01:16:37,960 --> 01:16:43,520
it in the context of the aspiration to become 
a multi-planetary species, but I think this is  

851
01:16:43,520 --> 01:16:50,760
true of every company, big or small. And there 
needs to be an aspirational and cool component  

852
01:16:50,760 --> 01:17:00,320
to strategy. And I call this big-S strategy.
I'll run through this at a higher level because  

853
01:17:00,320 --> 01:17:07,960
I think this is a little bit more fluid in how 
you build the big-S strategy. And it typically  

854
01:17:07,960 --> 01:17:15,160
takes longer, potentially up to about six months. 
The approach is a bit different from small S. And  

855
01:17:15,160 --> 01:17:21,760
you start with the company mission and vision, and 
there is a little bit of groundwork that is done  

856
01:17:21,760 --> 01:17:27,920
on long-term cultural trends, social trends, 
competitive trends, technological trends,  

857
01:17:27,920 --> 01:17:34,400
and those are all the backdrop to trigger ideas. 
And what you do with that backdrop is you, again,  

858
01:17:34,400 --> 01:17:41,280
do these leadership interviews, but with a 
different goal of generating long-term futures. 

859
01:17:41,280 --> 01:17:45,640
And some of the questions you can ask during 
these interviews are "What does a day in the  

860
01:17:45,640 --> 01:17:52,440
life of a user look like in five years? What does 
the product look like in five to 10 years? Why  

861
01:17:52,440 --> 01:17:58,440
is the world better in 10 years? And what is 
the most exciting version of that view?" And  

862
01:17:58,440 --> 01:18:05,360
basically take all of that input and cluster 
it into I would say, three cohesive holes. 

863
01:18:05,360 --> 01:18:11,720
And what I mean by that is three, at least fairly 
distinct, descriptions of the future. So to give  

864
01:18:11,720 --> 01:18:19,920
you almost a very simple example, imagine you 
doing big S for the future of travel. You could  

865
01:18:19,920 --> 01:18:27,160
have a future that is talking all about fully 
autonomous travel, where there's very little human  

866
01:18:27,160 --> 01:18:33,040
involvement in going from A to B. You could talk 
about another future where there's extreme speed,  

867
01:18:33,040 --> 01:18:37,960
where you can get from A to B really fast across 
the world that is really fast. You could talk  

868
01:18:37,960 --> 01:18:42,640
about a third where there is no travel, it's 
virtual travel, and you still have the feeling  

869
01:18:42,640 --> 01:18:47,720
of travel, and you accomplish the same goals.
But those are different futures, they have  

870
01:18:47,720 --> 01:18:52,920
different properties, like different elements 
to them. And once you generate those distinct  

871
01:18:52,920 --> 01:18:59,240
futures, you actually generate prototypes with 
learning goals. And think of these prototypes as  

872
01:18:59,240 --> 01:19:05,760
concept cars. And the automobile industry uses 
this notion of concept cars. Concept cars, the  

873
01:19:05,760 --> 01:19:13,360
interesting thing about concept cars is they're 
never commercialized. They're often produced for  

874
01:19:13,360 --> 01:19:20,560
inspiration, and to potentially take some part 
of them, like maybe a technology or a feature,  

875
01:19:20,560 --> 01:19:25,880
and that is brought into mainstream production.
So think of these prototypes as these concept cars  

876
01:19:25,880 --> 01:19:30,600
that really drive inspiration and potentially 
give you some small nuggets that you can run  

877
01:19:30,600 --> 01:19:37,360
with. And then you start doing research with them 
with potential users, you answer key questions,  

878
01:19:37,360 --> 01:19:41,720
and you uncover certain elements that 
resonate with people. So you eliminate  

879
01:19:41,720 --> 01:19:45,480
a whole bunch of stuff, you combine a 
whole bunch of stuff, and you establish  

880
01:19:45,480 --> 01:19:50,400
some winning components that are interesting.
And then what you do is you push stuff that  

881
01:19:50,400 --> 01:19:56,320
is winning into the product, live product, 
testing. So this is actually something that  

882
01:19:56,320 --> 01:20:01,720
you actually want to start testing your 
way into and understanding if it works  

883
01:20:01,720 --> 01:20:08,360
from a scalable standpoint. And this whole 
thing is typically led not by the PM team,  

884
01:20:08,360 --> 01:20:15,840
but by design and UXR. And intentionally it's 
a little bit more open-ended and green field.  

885
01:20:15,840 --> 01:20:24,080
And it actually is a very different mind space 
that people have when they approach big. So the  

886
01:20:24,080 --> 01:20:31,600
roadmap is really built through a combination 
of small-S and big-S work. And, for example,  

887
01:20:31,600 --> 01:20:37,440
at VRChat, we are doing both small-S and big-S 
work, Lenny. And they are run as parallel work  

888
01:20:37,440 --> 01:20:41,520
streams. The product management team is 
leading the charge of the small-S work,  

889
01:20:41,520 --> 01:20:45,920
and the design team is leading the charge on the 
big-S work. And it's really exciting stuff. What's  

890
01:20:45,920 --> 01:20:51,600
coming out of both work streams is really exciting 
and really different. And so we are building the  

891
01:20:51,600 --> 01:20:56,560
bridge from both sides and both work streams 
ultimately flow into one roadmap. It's almost  

892
01:20:56,560 --> 01:21:01,038
like two tributaries that ultimately merge into 
one river. That's how I would think about it.

893
01:21:01,038 --> 01:21:01,080
There's so many things here that are so...

894
01:21:01,080 --> 01:21:02,320
That's how I would think about it.

895
01:21:02,320 --> 01:21:06,120
There's so many things here that are so 
interesting. One is we've had this conversation  

