01:21:06,120 --> 01:21:11,960
on the podcast a couple of times, this point that 
people think and see the world differently. Some  

897
01:21:11,960 --> 01:21:19,200
people are very open-minded and creative, and 
think big, blue sky people. Some people, me, just  

898
01:21:19,200 --> 01:21:23,400
like, "What are we doing next? How do we move this 
metric? Let's talk about concrete things that we  

899
01:21:23,400 --> 01:21:29,840
can do?" For this big S approach, I think what 
I'm hearing is make sure the people leading it  

900
01:21:29,840 --> 01:21:34,240
are very open-minded, creative, blue sky type 
people. If you're the person that's like, "How  

901
01:21:34,240 --> 01:21:40,480
will this move our metric?" Maybe you shouldn't 
be leading it and give someone else the reins. 

902
01:21:40,480 --> 01:21:44,920
Cool. And then with these timelines of 
doing both at once, it's probably hard  

903
01:21:44,920 --> 01:21:49,360
to align them fully. So what I'm hearing is 
it's like these are kind of ongoing sometimes.

904
01:21:49,360 --> 01:21:50,400
Correct.

905
01:21:50,400 --> 01:21:54,600
And they'll both inform what you're doing. You 
don't need to have this perfect timeline of-

906
01:21:54,600 --> 01:21:56,400
I agree to this. Yeah.

907
01:21:56,400 --> 01:22:03,520
Sweet. And the big thinking I love, 
because sometimes, you may experience this,  

908
01:22:03,520 --> 01:22:07,600
designers often are like, "Oh, we just work 
on all this boring, incremental optimization  

909
01:22:07,600 --> 01:22:12,880
stuff. I want to think bigger." Which is 
great, and this is a really good lever to  

